Source: Health Canada [edited]

[A] Update: severe acute respiratory syndrome (SARS) 13 Apr 2003 4:00 PM
Latest Canadian Numbers on SARS
As of 13 Apr 2003, Health Canada has received reports of 283 probable or
suspect cases of severe acute respiratory syndrome (SARS) in Canada. There
have been 13 deaths in Canada. All Canadian cases have occurred in persons
who have traveled to Asia or had contact with SARS cases in the household
or in a health-care setting. The information contained in this update is
based on the best available information Health Canada has at this time.
The details of the cases to date are as follows:
Ontario is reporting 97 probable and 135 suspect cases. All cases have
occurred in persons who have traveled to Asia or had contact with SARS
cases in the household or in a health-care setting.
British Columbia is reporting 3 probable and 36 suspect cases.
New Brunswick is reporting 2 suspect cases.
Saskatchewan is reporting 1 suspect case.
Alberta is reporting 5 suspect cases.
Prince Edward Island is reporting 4 suspect cases.
So far, 55 people have been discharged from hospitals in Ontario. These
people were treated as suspect cases or as probable cases.
These numbers are accurate as of 1:00 PM EDST 13 Apr 2003.
[B] Epidemiologic analysis of outbreak
<http://www.hc-sc.gc.ca/pphb-dgspsp/sars-sras/prof_e.html>
[Information on epidemiologic analyses of the outbreak of SARS in Toronto
are available via the above given link. The data available as of today are
current through 12 Apr 2003 and can be accessed at:
<http://www.hc-sc.gc.ca/pphb-dgspsp/sars-sras/eu-ae/sars20030412_e.html>.
Interested readers are urged to check out the available data, as it
contains an excellent epidemic curve current through 2 Apr 2003 based on
date of onset of illness of cases, and type of contact transmission
(travellers, healthcare-related exposure, index case household contact,
healthcare-related exposure household contact).
According to the analyses to date, the conclusion is "there is currently no
evidence to suggest the presence community transmission of SARS in Canada.
All identified probable cases of SARS have been linked to either
travel-related exposures, or in healthcare and household settings."
Additional information of interest from this presentation is given below. -
Mod.MPP]
Since yesterday, no additional probable cases of SARS have been reported in
Canada. A total of 100 individuals who meet the probable case definition of
SARS have been reported in Ontario and British Columbia, including 13
deaths; 174 individuals who meet the definition of a suspect case of SARS
have also been reported in British Columbia, Alberta, Saskatchewan,
Ontario, New Brunswick, and Prince Edward Island. Since SARS is a diagnosis
of exclusion, the status of a reported case may change over time.
At the present time, the case fatality rate in Canada is estimated at
approximately 4.7 percent of probable or suspect cases (13 of 274 probable
or suspect cases). Most of the case fatalities occurred in patients with
underlying illness, and nearly all were elderly patients over the age of 70
years.
Table 2: Currently reported status of probable cases of SARS in Canada: 12
Apr 2003
(N=97, excluding 3 for whom status is unknown)
Current Status: No./total in category (percent)
Hospitalised: 62/97 (64 percent)
- Improving: 13/62 (21 percent)
- Stable: 29/62 (47 percent)
- Critical/Deteriorating: 7/62 (11 percent)
- Unknown: 13/62 (21 percent)
Discharged(1): 25/97 (26 percent)
Deceased: 13/97 (13 percent)
Total: 97 (100 percent)
(1) Includes cases who have either recovered or are recovering
Table 3: Type of exposure to probable cases of SARS in Canada: 11 Apr 2003
Exposure type: No. cases (percent of total cases)
Hospital or healthcare-related setting: 72 (74 percent)
Household: 19 (19 percent)
Travel: 7 ( 7 percent)
Total 98 (100 percent)
