[Hong Kong reported 42 new cases in the 24 hours since the last
report. More detailed information on the epidemiology of these cases was
not provided, other than the data that 9 of the new cases were health care
workers, 5 were residents of Amoy Gardens (the residence associated with
unusual transmission), and the remaining 28 newly reported cases were in
known contacts of previously diagnosed SARS patients and new patients. The
number of new patients is not specified, nor is the definition of possible
exposure risks of these new patients given (e.g., are there other apartment
blocks that are showing up epidemiologically to have increased numbers of
cases? As a reminder, there is a posted list of apartment blocks where
SARS cases have been identified on the Hong Kong Department of Health
website <http://www.info.gov.hk/dh/ap.htm>). We look forward to seeing
more detailed epidemiologic analyses of the current transmission patterns
in Hong Kong.
We have included the report from Singapore in depth as a demonstration of
their intense effort towards disease control. From the reduced numbers of
new cases reported on a daily basis, it appears as though these efforts
have been reasonably successful.
For those who are interested in PowerPoint presentations summarizing the
epidemiologic points from investigations of the ongoing outbreak, we
suggest visiting the CDC website:
<http://www.cdc.gov/ncidod/sars/ppt/domesticsars.ppt> for information on
the USA and <http://www.cdc.gov/ncidod/sars/ppt/globalsars.ppt> for
information on the global outbreak.
Global updates on SARS cases were not available at the WHO SARS website as
of 8:00 PM EDST (2:00 AM GMT +2 Geneva time). Similarly an update on the
status of SARS cases in the USA was not available on the CDC SARS website
as of 8:00 PM EDST. Additionally, the lay press reports did not contain
additional information that would add to this current posting or earlier
postings, other than a quote in the NY Times from one of the WHO team
leaders, Dr. James Maguire, while visiting hospitals in Beijing: "If there
had been hundreds of SARS patients, it would have been very difficult to
hide them," in response to press speculation that there was significant
underreporting in Beijing.
(<http://www.nytimes.com/2003/04/13/international/asia/13CHIN.html>) This
quote was given after the team visited Chaoyang Hospital, a large general
hospital that has seen some patients with the new ailment. We await more
official details on the results of the epidemiologic investigations in
China. - Mod.MPP]
[Please note that the number of prior postings on SARS is too numerous to
include in the references section below. The large size of each posting is
due to the extensive amount of new information being generated on a daily
basis. For those who have not been receiving these postings in emails and
are interested in following the history and evolution of SARS, we strongly
suggest you visit our website at: <http://www.promedmail.org> and follow
the update information in the designated SARS "box". In addition, the
postings before the name "severe acute respiratory syndrome (SARS)" was
given to this observed clinical syndrome can be found by linking on the
last reference for each thread (e.g., Pneumonia - China (Guandong) (07),
and then linking to the given references. - Mod.MPP]
